1NARRATIVE0
.adjust
Purpose^^^^^We have seen pre-school children entering a new relation with the alphabetic language through their use of computers, a relation where alphabetic symbols work for their purposes as never before possible.  We will construct an intelligent videodisc system -- the word worlds  machine -- for use by pre-readers.  Keying alphabetic symbols will execute computer functions, among which will be accessing pictures stored on videodisc.  We will explore how this early  generative use of alphabetic symbols affects the development of children's reading and writing ability.

Execution^^^^^First, we will attach videodisc hardware to existing computers in our laboratory.  We will design files of pictures and computer access methods for retrieving them.  After testing the interface and access methods with commercially available videodiscs, we will assemble the materials for the picture files and have an education research disc manufactured.  Following preliminary observation of children's interactions with this system during the first year of its development, we will place the word worlds machine in a nursery school environment the second year.   There, by naturalistic observation, analysis of computer system logs, and through care-taker reports we will trace how the experience affects the alphabetic language ability of the children.

Significance^^^^^The word worlds machine could make the written language truly functional for a pre-reader -- a novelty of the first order.  This change could bring into synchronization the development of reading and writing and thus make it possible for children to master the alphabetic language as they now learn the vocal language, through the interaction of production and interpretation.  Such a change could be beneficial for all children but would do the most good for those who most need it -- the children who for whatever reason have trouble with writing and reading.
