 Facilities and Arrangements^

^^^^^^^^^^Situated where it began, in the midst of a major computer facility (the M.I.T. Artificial Intelligence Laboratory), the Logo Project continues to study the impact of computer technology on children's minds and to develop frontier technology systems for their humane education.  (The Piagetian and computer culture roots of Logo are described in Papert, 1980a.)  Recently, we have produced versions of the Logo language for several microcomputers (TI-99 and Apple; others are being considered).  Microcomputers on which the development has been based will be available at no charge as the Logo computer of the word worlds machine.

^^^^^^^^^^No need is anticipated during the development phase for arranging formal access to research "subjects".  Peggy Lawler, the three year old daughter of the research associate, will join the Logo Project.  We are quite confident of our ability to construct a system which she will find engaging and do believe her reactions will provide good, preliminary testing.  Further, we have many visitors to the Project and anticipate no problem in finding children on a casual basis for preliminary testing during the development year.

^^^^^^^^^^Formal arrangements will be made for access to research subjects during the late spring of 1982.  We have discussed the concept of such a system with several people in primary education.  Their interest was considerable and some inquired whether we might consider their schools as a possible site.  It would be premature to go further with such discussions until the Spring of 1982.  By then we will be able to demonstrate the word worlds machine to those who could decide to place it in their  environment.  
